We have recommended that Management:

Instruct the Inventory Committee and GSO to complete the physical count of all PPEs and furnish complete reports using the prescribed format of the RPCPPE;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to prepare the PPELCs and PCs, respectively, and thereafter ensure regular reconciliation thereof and other related records;

Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare / maintain Subsidiary Ledgers for each class of PPE account to provide details or breakdown of and to support the balances appearing in the General Ledger;

Direct the Inventory Committee, Property Custodian and the Municipal Accountant to conduct reconciliation of data in the RPCPPE with the accounting and property records to address the above variances/differences and prevent occurrence of the same; and

Consider conducting the one-time cleansing of PPE in which upon completion of the proper conduct of physical count:

Instruct the Supply Officer to determine the person/s accountable for any non-existing/missing PPEs based on the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs), PCs and other available property records, and thereafter issue demand letters to produce the missing PPE; and

Direct the Inventory Team, the Supply Officer and the Municipal Accountant to refer to Sections 7 to 9 of the same COA circular for the procedures in the disposition and derecognition of any non-existing/missing PPEs.

We have recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to record purchases of supplies/materials for stock under the appropriate Inventory Account;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to prepare the SLCs (Annex A) for each commodity/stock and Stock Cards (Annex B), respectively, and thereafter ensure regular reconciliation thereof and other related records;

Strictly require the weekly preparation of SSMI (Annex C) to support the recognition of supplies/materials issuances as expenses pursuant to Section 121 of NGAS Manual Vol. 1;

Instruct the Inventory Committee and GSO to conduct semestral physical count of inventory items by type and submit the required Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI) (Annex D) to the auditor;

For the Drugs and Medicines and Accountable Forms Inventory, instruct the Municipal Hospital Administrator and the Municipal Treasurer to maintain Stock Cards and SSMI, respectively, to properly account the receipts and issuances of the inventories; and

Consider the necessary revisions in the pertinent disclosure in the Notes to the FS which is inconsistent with what is really being practiced by the agency relative to the recognition of purchases of supplies / materials.

We have recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to appropriately recognize Leave Benefits Payable and TLB in the books;

Maximize the revenue-raising power of the municipality to identify additional source of revenue to fund the whole amount of payables.

We recommended the management to:

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment and require the submission of the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) giving priority to its Lands and, if possible, provide additional manpower to its inventory taking process in order to assure its completion and submission; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant and Property Officer to establish its own Subsidiary Ledgers and corresponding Property Ledger Cards for each parcel of land and further reconcile the PPE balances once the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) is completed and submitted in compliance with Section 120 - Vol. 1 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs;

Exhaust all possible means to document the legality of ownership over all parcel of lands through Transfer Certificate of Titles (TCT) in the name of the Municipality and to ensure that the LGU has legal rights over all recognized assets in its financial statements.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Issue a memorandum for all collectors/tellers and the Municipal Treasurer to enforce daily/prompt and intact remittance and deposit all collections, and to impose sanctions against erring collectors/AOs pursuant to pertinent laws, rules and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to closely and regularly monitor the remittances by collectors/tellers and stop the practice of incomplete deposit and the use of collections for payment of urgent obligations, disbursements and advances as well as for encashment of payroll checks;
Review its internal control processes on the manner of collections and remittance and institute measures to curtail the delay in the deposits of these collections;
Provide transportation to ensure regular availability of the same to be used in the deposit of collections and other bank transactions; and
Open a bank account at a nearby Authorized Government Depository Bank to reduce long trips and facilitate the prompt deposit of collections.

7.10 We recommended and Management concurred to the following:
7.10.1 Prepare and fast track the reconciliation of the taxes withheld and remitted for CY 2024 and take appropriate actions to ensure full remittance thereof within the prescribed period and take up necessary adjustments in the books and related records/BIR forms;
7.10.2 Ensure correct and prompt remittance of taxes withheld to avoid unnecessary penalties;
7.10.3  Set a cut-off for the submission of Abstract of Collections and RCDs by the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to the Municipal Accounting Office;
7.10.4  Institute measures to improve the withholding and remittance of taxes to ensure that the unremitted taxes at year-end only include those withheld during the last month of the year;
7.10.5  Institute measures to recover the penalty and interest incurred for the November 2024 DST remittances from the responsible employees; and
7.10.6 Review / assess the roles of personnel assigned in the reconciliation of the discrepancies, and consider assigning additional staff to expedite the process.

We recommended and that Management concurred to direct the Municipal Accountant to: 
Prepare and fast track the reconciliation of the unadjusted/ unidentified Due to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth account balances to identify under/over remittances, and take appropriate actions to ensure full remittance thereof within the prescribed period and/or make refunds to concerned employees, if warranted;
Ensure thereafter that all applicable contributions and loan payments are remitted timely to avoid late payment charges, interests and penalties.  Also, make sure that such remittances / payments are accurately reflected in the bank without reversals;
Ensure that reconciling items identified are properly and adjusted accordingly and promptly;
Set a deadline for the online processing and payment of withheld contributions, loan repayments, and remittances by the HR Department, and ensure immediate coordination with MTO personnel for timely approval of online payments to prevent delays and the incurrence of penalties;
Institute measures to recover the penalty and interest incurred for the May, July and September 2024 PhilHealth remittances from the responsible employees; and
Review / assess the roles of personnel assigned in the reconciliation of the discrepancies, and consider assigning additional staff to expedite the process.

